I really, really, really like the bit at the end about the recessive nature of the anomaly. Recessive mutations reach fixation much slower than dominant or codominant mutations, but increase the most steeply when they finally gain enough  so to speak. One of my favorite instances of Paretto curves. Honestly, why not explore that a bit? You could add some diagrams going into the evolutionary mechanics of allele fixation and help folks understand WHY this is keter-class.

Easy +1 for decent concept and great execution.







